{"id":"mai-eu3f","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"You are a test engineer. Your job: write comprehensive regression tests for the new `mai pr` workflow in the maitake project.\n\n## Working Directory\n\nYou're in a Go project at the repo root. Tests live in `test/` as Go integration tests.\n\n## What to test\n\nThe PR workflow was just implemented in `cmd/mai/pr.go`. Read that file first, then read `cmd/mai/main.go` (the `dispatchPR` function), then read the existing test infrastructure in `test/cli_test.go` to understand the test helpers (`mai()`, `maiFail()`, `setupTestRepo()`, `gitRun()`).\n\n## Test file\n\nCreate `test/pr_test.go` with comprehensive tests. Use the SAME test helpers from `cli_test.go` — `mai()`, `maiFail()`, `setupTestRepo()`, `gitRun()` are already available (same package `test`).\n\n## CRITICAL: Creating branches for PR tests\n\nPR tests need source and target branches with actual divergent commits. The setup pattern:\n```go\ndir := setupTestRepo(t)  // creates repo on default branch with initial commit\n// setupTestRepo leaves you on the default branch (usually 'main' or 'master')\n// Check what the default branch is:\n// gitRun(t, dir, \"branch\", \"--show-current\") \n// For reliability, RENAME the branch to 'main':\ngitRun(t, dir, \"branch\", \"-M\", \"main\")\n// Create a feature branch with a commit:\ngitRun(t, dir, \"checkout\", \"-b\", \"feature/auth\")\nos.WriteFile(filepath.Join(dir, \"src\", \"new.ts\"), []byte(\"new file\"), 0644)\ngitRun(t, dir, \"add\", \"-A\")\ngitRun(t, dir, \"commit\", \"-m\", \"add new feature\")\n```\n\n## Test cases to cover (ALL of these, no skipping)\n\n### Happy path\n1. Create PR, verify output has ID and branch arrows\n2. List PRs, verify created PR appears\n3. Show PR — verify title, branches, status, review pending\n4. Show PR with --diff — verify diff output appears\n5. Show PR with --json — verify JSON format\n6. Accept PR — verify output, then show confirms accepted status\n7. Reject PR — verify output, then show confirms rejected + message visible\n8. Accept after reject — verify review flips back to accepted\n9. Submit PR — verify merge happens, PR closed\n10. Diff PR — verify actual diff content between branches\n11. Diff PR --stat — verify stat summary\n12. Comment on PR — verify comment appears in show\n13. Comment with --file and --line — verify file-located comment\n\n### Auto-close\n14. Create PR, manually merge the branch with git, then `mai pr` list — verify auto-close happened\n15. Submit already-merged PR — should just close without merge error\n\n### Error cases\n16. PR on detached HEAD — should fail\n17. PR with same source and target branch — should fail\n18. Show non-existent PR — should fail\n19. Show a ticket (not a PR) via `pr show` — should fail with 'not a PR'\n20. Reject without message — should fail\n21. Submit with unresolved comments — should fail\n22. Submit with --force overrides unresolved check\n23. Submit already-closed PR — should fail\n24. Diff on non-PR — should fail\n25. Accept non-PR — should fail\n\n### Edge cases\n26. PR with no title (auto-generates 'branch → target')\n27. Multiple PRs listed at once\n28. PR list when no PRs exist — 'No open PRs.'\n29. PR comment uses -m flag correctly (message NOT prefixed with '-m')\n\n## Build and run\n\n```bash\nnix-shell -p go --run 'go test ./test/ -count=1 -timeout 180s -run TestPR -v'\n```\n\nFix any test failures. ALL tests must pass. Also make sure existing tests still pass:\n```bash\nnix-shell -p go --run 'go test ./... -count=1 -timeout 180s'\n```\n\n## Rules\n- Use the existing test helpers. Don't reinvent them.\n- Each test function should be independent (own repo setup).\n- Test names: `TestPR_Create`, `TestPR_Show`, `TestPR_AcceptReject`, `TestPR_Submit`, `TestPR_AutoClose`, `TestPR_Errors`, etc.\n- Group related assertions into subtests with `t.Run()`.\n- Check BOTH stdout content AND side effects (e.g., after submit, verify the git branch was actually merged).\n- 